# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phoenix-liveview
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] The community organizes yearly events in the United States, Europe, and Japan, as well as minor local events and conferences.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] José Valim created the Elixir programming language as a research and development project at Plataformatec.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] His goals were to enable higher extensibility and productivity in the Erlang VM while maintaining compatibility with Erlang's ecosystem.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] Elixir is aimed at large-scale sites and apps.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] It uses features of Ruby, Erlang, and Clojure to develop a high-concurrency and low-latency language.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] It was designed to handle large data volumes.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] Elixir is also used in telecommunications, e-commerce, and finance.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] In 2021, the Numerical Elixir effort was announced with the goal of bringing machine learning, neural networks, GPU compilation, data processing, and computational notebooks to the Elixir ecosystem.
[src:phoenix-liveview/elixir-programming-language] The following examples can be run in an `iex` shell or saved in a file and run from the command line by typing `elixir *<filename>*`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang programming language has data, pattern matching, and functional programming.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The sequential subset of the Erlang language supports eager evaluation, single assignment, and dynamic typing.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A normal Erlang application is built out of hundreds of small Erlang processes.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] It was originally proprietary software within Ericsson, developed by Joe Armstrong, Robert Virding, and Mike Williams in 1986, but was released as free and open-source software in 1998.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang/OTP is supported and maintained by the Open Telecom Platform (OTP) product unit at Ericsson.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The name *Erlang*, attributed to Bjarne Däcker, has been presumed by those working on the telephony switches (for whom the language was designed) to be a reference to Danish mathematician and engineer Agner Krarup Erlang and a syllabic abbreviation of "Ericsson Language".
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang was designed with the aim of improving the development of telephony applications.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The initial version of Erlang was implemented in Prolog and was influenced by the programming language PLEX used in earlier Ericsson exchanges.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] By 1988 Erlang had proven that it was suitable for prototyping telephone exchanges, but the Prolog interpreter was far too slow.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] One group within Ericsson estimated that it would need to be 40 times faster to be suitable for production use.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In 1992, work began on the BEAM virtual machine (VM), which compiles Erlang to C using a mix of natively compiled code and threaded code to strike a balance between performance and disk space.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] According to co-inventor Joe Armstrong, the language went from laboratory product to real applications following the collapse of the next-generation AXE telephone exchange named *AXE-N* in 1995.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] As a result, Erlang was chosen for the next Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) exchange *AXD*.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In February 1998, Ericsson Radio Systems banned the in-house use of Erlang for new products, citing a preference for non-proprietary languages.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The ban caused Armstrong and others to make plans to leave Ericsson.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In March 1998 Ericsson announced the AXD301 switch, containing over a million lines of Erlang and reported to achieve a high availability of nine "9"s.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In December 1998, the implementation of Erlang was open-sourced and most of the Erlang team resigned to form a new company, Bluetail AB.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson eventually relaxed the ban and re-hired Armstrong in 2004.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In 2006, native symmetric multiprocessing support was added to the runtime system and VM.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang applications are built of very lightweight Erlang processes in the Erlang runtime system.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang runtime system provides strict process isolation between Erlang processes (this includes data and garbage collection, separated individually by each Erlang process) and transparent communication between processes (see Location transparency) on different Erlang nodes (on different hosts).
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In 2014, Ericsson reported Erlang was being used in its support nodes, and in GPRS, 3G and LTE mobile networks worldwide and also by Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is the programming language used to code WhatsApp.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] It is also the language of choice for Ejabberd – an XMPP messaging server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Elixir is a programming language that compiles into BEAM byte code (via Erlang Abstract Format).
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Since being released as open source, Erlang has been spreading beyond telecoms, establishing itself in other vertical markets such as FinTech, gaming, healthcare, automotive, Internet of Things and blockchain.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Apart from WhatsApp, there are other companies listed as Erlang's success stories, including Vocalink (a MasterCard company), Goldman Sachs, Nintendo, AdRoll, Grindr, BT Mobile, Samsung, OpenX, and SITA.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Omitting the comments gives a much shorter program.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The above example recursively invokes the function `qsort` until nothing remains to be sorted.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The expression `[Front || Front <- Rest, Front < Pivot]` is a list comprehension, meaning "Construct a list of elements `Front` such that `Front` is a member of `Rest`, and `Front` is less than `Pivot`." `++` is the list concatenation operator.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A comparison function can be used for more complicated structures for the sake of readability.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A `Pivot` is taken from the first parameter given to `qsort()` and the rest of `Lists` is named `Rest`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The anonymous function is named `Smaller` in the parameter list of the second definition of `qsort` so that it can be referenced by that name within that function.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] It is not named in the first definition of `qsort`, which deals with the base case of an empty list and thus has no need of this function, let alone a name for it.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Integers are written as sequences of decimal digits, for example, 12, 12375 and -23427 are integers.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Integer arithmetic is exact and only limited by available memory on the machine.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are used within a program to denote distinguished values.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] They are written as strings of consecutive alphanumeric characters, the first character being lowercase.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Atoms can contain any character if they are enclosed within single quotes and an escape convention exists which allows any character to be used within an atom.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are never garbage collected and should be used with caution, especially if using dynamic atom generation.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] References are globally unique symbols whose only property is that they can be compared for equality.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Binaries provide a space-efficient way of storing binary data.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang primitives exist for composing and decomposing binaries and for efficient input/output of binaries.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Pids are references to Erlang processes.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Ports are used to communicate with the external world.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Tuples are containers for a fixed number of Erlang data types.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The arguments can be primitive data types or compound data types.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Any element of a tuple can be accessed in constant time.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Lists are containers for a variable number of Erlang data types.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The first element of a list can be accessed in constant time.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Maps contain a variable number of key-value associations.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Strings are written as doubly quoted lists of characters.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] code points for the characters in the string.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Records provide a convenient way for associating a tag with each of the elements in a tuple.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] This allows one to refer to an element of a tuple by name and not by position.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A pre-compiler takes the record definition and replaces it with the appropriate tuple reference.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is designed with a mechanism that makes it easy for external processes to monitor for crashes (or hardware failures), rather than an in-process mechanism like exception handling used in many other programming languages.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Crashes are reported like other messages, which is the only way processes can communicate with each other, and subprocesses can be spawned cheaply (see below).
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The "let it crash" philosophy prefers that a process be completely restarted rather than trying to recover from a serious failure.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Though it still requires handling of errors, this philosophy results in less code devoted to defensive programming where error-handling code is highly contextual and specific.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A typical Erlang application is written in the form of a supervisor tree.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] This architecture is based on a hierarchy of processes in which the top level process is known as a "supervisor".
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor then spawns multiple child processes that act either as workers or more, lower level supervisors.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Such hierarchies can exist to arbitrary depths and have proven to provide a highly scalable and fault-tolerant environment within which application functionality can be implemented.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Within a supervisor tree, all supervisor processes are responsible for managing the lifecycle of their child processes, and this includes handling situations in which those child processes crash.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Any process can become a supervisor by first spawning a child process, then calling `erlang:monitor/2` on that process.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] If the monitored process then crashes, the supervisor will receive a message containing a tuple whose first member is the atom `'DOWN'`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor is responsible firstly for listening for such messages and for taking the appropriate action to correct the error condition.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang's main strength is support for concurrency.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] It has a small but powerful set of primitives to create processes and communicate among them.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is conceptually similar to the language occam, though it recasts the ideas of communicating sequential processes (CSP) in a functional framework and uses asynchronous message passing.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Processes are the primary means to structure an Erlang application.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] They are neither operating system processes nor threads, but lightweight processes that are scheduled by BEAM.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Like operating system processes (but unlike operating system threads), they share no state with each other.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The estimated minimal overhead for each is 300 words.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Thus, many processes can be created without degrading performance.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In 2005, a benchmark with 20 million processes was successfully performed with 64-bit Erlang on a machine with 16 GB random-access memory (RAM; total 800 bytes/process).
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has supported symmetric multiprocessing since release R11B of May 2006.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] While threads need external library support in most languages, Erlang provides language-level features to create and manage processes with the goal of simplifying concurrent programming.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Though all concurrency is explicit in Erlang, processes communicate using message passing instead of shared variables, which removes the need for explicit locks (a locking scheme is still used internally by the VM).
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Inter-process communication works via a shared-nothing asynchronous message passing system: every process has a "mailbox", a queue of messages that have been sent by other processes and not yet consumed.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A process uses the `receive` primitive to retrieve messages that match desired patterns.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A message-handling routine tests messages in turn against each pattern, until one of them matches.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] When the message is consumed and removed from the mailbox the process resumes execution.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A message may comprise any Erlang structure, including primitives (integers, floats, characters, atoms), tuples, lists, and functions.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] As the example shows, processes may be created on remote nodes, and communication with them is transparent in the sense that communication with remote processes works exactly as communication with local processes.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Concurrency supports the primary method of error-handling in Erlang.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] When a process crashes, it neatly exits and sends a message to the controlling process which can then take action, such as starting a new process that takes over the old process's task.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The official reference implementation of Erlang uses BEAM.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] BEAM is included in the official distribution of Erlang, called Erlang/OTP.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] BEAM executes bytecode which is converted to threaded code at load time.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] It also includes a native code compiler on most platforms, developed by the High Performance Erlang Project (HiPE) at Uppsala University.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Since October 2001 the HiPE system is fully integrated in Ericsson's Open Source Erlang/OTP system.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] It also supports interpreting, directly from source code via abstract syntax tree, via script as of R11B-5 release of Erlang.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang supports language-level Dynamic Software Updating.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] To implement this, code is loaded and managed as "module" units; the module is a compilation unit.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The system can keep two versions of a module in memory at the same time, and processes can concurrently run code from each.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The versions are referred to as the "new" and the "old" version.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] A process will not move into the new version until it makes an external call to its module.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] For the second version, we add the possibility to reset the count to zero.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Only when receiving a message consisting of the atom `code_switch` will the loop execute an external call to codeswitch/1 (`?MODULE` is a preprocessor macro for the current module).
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] If there is a new version of the *counter* module in memory, then its codeswitch/1 function will be called.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] The practice of having a specific entry-point into a new version allows the programmer to transform state to what is needed in the newer version.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In the example, the state is kept as an integer.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In practice, systems are built up using design principles from the Open Telecom Platform, which leads to more code upgradable designs.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Successful hot code loading is exacting.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Code must be written with care to make use of Erlang's facilities.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] In 1998, Ericsson released Erlang as free and open-source software to ensure its independence from a single vendor and to increase awareness of the language.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang, together with libraries and the real-time distributed database Mnesia, forms the OTP collection of libraries.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson and a few other companies support Erlang commercially.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Since the open source release, Erlang has been used by several firms worldwide, including Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Although Erlang was designed to fill a niche and has remained an obscure language for most of its existence, its popularity is growing due to demand for concurrent services.
[src:phoenix-liveview/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has found some use in fielding massively multiplayer online role-playing game (MMORPG) servers.
[src:phoenix-liveview/phoenix-web-framework] Phoenix uses a server-side model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:phoenix-liveview/phoenix-web-framework] Based on the Plug library, and ultimately the Erlang HTTP server Cowboy, it was developed to provide highly performant and scalable web applications.
[src:phoenix-liveview/phoenix-web-framework] In addition to the request/response functionality provided by the underlying Cowboy server, Phoenix provides soft realtime communication to external clients through WebSockets or long polling using its language agnostic channels feature.
[src:phoenix-liveview/phoenix-web-framework] Two notable features of Phoenix are LiveView and HEEx.
[src:phoenix-liveview/phoenix-web-framework] LiveView provides real-time user experiences with server-rendered HTML over HTTP and WebSocket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/phoenix-web-framework] HEEx is Phoenix's templating language which provides HTML-aware compile time checking.
[src:phoenix-liveview/server-sent-events] All modern browsers support server-sent events: Firefox 6+, Google Chrome 6+, Opera 11.5+, Safari 5+, Microsoft Edge 79+, Brave.
[src:phoenix-liveview/server-sent-events] Since SSE does not use either persistent connections nor chunked transfer encoding, HTTP/1.1 is not a technical requirement.
[src:phoenix-liveview/server-sent-events] The SSE mechanism was first specified by Ian Hickson as part of the "WHATWG Web Applications 1.0" proposal starting in 2004.
[src:phoenix-liveview/server-sent-events] In September 2006, the Opera web browser implemented the experimental technology in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:phoenix-liveview/server-sent-events] The W3C published Server-Sent Events as a Recommendation on February 3, 2015, after years of development through Working Drafts and Candidate Recommendations.
[src:phoenix-liveview/server-sent-events] When sending high-frequency data , the server must manage backpressure to prevent saturating clients.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] For readability, the code ignores that, thus it may fail in non-ideal network conditions.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:phoenix-liveview/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Welcome to Phoenix LiveView documentation.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Phoenix LiveView enables rich, real-time user experiences with server-rendered HTML.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] A general overview of LiveView and its benefits is available in our README.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveViews are processes that receive events, update their state, and render updates to a page as diffs.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The LiveView programming model is declarative: instead of saying "once event X happens, change Y on the page", events in LiveView are regular messages which may cause changes to the state.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Once the state changes, the LiveView will re-render the relevant parts of its HTML template and push it to the browser, which updates the page in the most efficient manner.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveView state is nothing more than functional and immutable Elixir data structures.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The events are either internal application messages (usually emitted by `Phoenix.PubSub`) or sent by the client/browser.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Every LiveView is first rendered statically as part of a regular HTTP request, which provides quick times for "First Meaningful Paint", in addition to helping search and indexing engines.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] A persistent connection is then established between the client and server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] This allows LiveView applications to react faster to user events as there is less work to be done and less data to be sent compared to stateless requests that have to authenticate, decode, load, and encode data on every request.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveView is included by default in Phoenix applications.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Therefore, to use LiveView, you must have already installed Phoenix and created your first application.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] If you haven't done so, check Phoenix' installation guide to get started.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The behaviour of a LiveView is outlined by a module which implements a series of functions as callbacks.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Write the file below to `lib/my_app_web/live/thermostat_live.ex`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The module above defines three functions (they are callbacks required by LiveView).
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The first one is `render/1`, which receives the socket `assigns` and is responsible for returning the content to be rendered on the page.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] We use the `~H` sigil to define a HEEx template, which stands for HTML+EEx.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] They are an extension of Elixir's builtin EEx templates, with support for HTML validation, syntax-based components, smart change tracking, and more.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] You can learn more about the template syntax in `Phoenix.Component.sigil_H/2` (note `Phoenix.Component` is automatically imported when you use `Phoenix.LiveView`).
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The data used on rendering comes from the `mount` callback.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The `mount` callback is invoked when the LiveView starts.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] In it, you can access the request parameters, read information stored in the session (typically information which identifies who is the current user), and a socket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The socket is where we keep all state, including assigns.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] `mount` proceeds to assign a default temperature to the socket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Because Elixir data structures are immutable, LiveView APIs often receive the socket and return an updated socket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Then we return `{:ok, socket}` to signal that we were able to mount the LiveView successfully.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] After `mount`, LiveView will render the page with the values from `assigns` and send it to the client.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] If you look at the HTML rendered, you will notice there is a button with a `phx-click` attribute.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] When the button is clicked, a `"inc_temperature"` event is sent to the server, which is matched and handled by the `handle_event` callback.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] This callback updates the socket and returns `{:noreply, socket}` with the updated socket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] `handle_*` callbacks in LiveView (and in Elixir in general) are invoked based on some action, in this case, the user clicking a button.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The `{:noreply, socket}` return means there is no additional replies sent to the browser, only that a new version of the page is rendered.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveView then computes diffs and sends them to the client.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Now we are ready to render our LiveView.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Once the LiveView is rendered, a regular HTML response is sent.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Because of this, the JavaScript client will connect over WebSockets and `mount/3` will be invoked inside a spawned LiveView process.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The mount callback receives three arguments: the request parameters, the session, and the socket.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The parameters can be used to read information from the URL.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The session retrieves information from a signed (or encrypted) cookie.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] In other words, you want to read the information about a given house, as long as the user has access to it.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Phoenix supports DOM element bindings for client-server interaction.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] To update UI state, for example, to open and close dropdowns, switch tabs, etc, LiveView also supports JS commands (`Phoenix.LiveView.JS`), which execute directly on the client without reaching the server.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] To learn more, see our bindings page for a complete list of all LiveView bindings as well as our JavaScript interoperability guide.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveView has built-in support for forms, including uploads and association management.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] See `Phoenix.Component.form/1` as a starting point and `Phoenix.Component.inputs_for/1` for working with associations.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] The Uploads and Form bindings guides provide more information about advanced features.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveView provides functionality to allow page navigation using the browser's pushState API.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] With live navigation, the page is updated without a full page reload.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] You can either *patch* the current LiveView, updating its URL, or *navigate* to a new LiveView.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] You can learn more about them in the Live Navigation guide.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Phoenix v1.6 and later includes code generators for LiveView.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] For more information, run `mix help phx.gen.live`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] For authentication, with built-in LiveView support, run `mix phx.gen.auth Account User users`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveView supports two extension mechanisms: function components, provided by `HEEx` templates, and stateful components, known as LiveComponents.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Similar to `render(assigns)` in our LiveView, a function component is any function that receives an assigns map and returns a `~H` template.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] You can learn more about function components in the `Phoenix.Component` module.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] At the end of the day, they are a useful mechanism for code organization and to reuse markup in your LiveViews.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Sometimes you need to share more than just markup across LiveViews.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] When you also want to move events to a separate module, or use the same event handler in multiple places, function components can be paired with `Phoenix.LiveView.attach_hook/4`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] A component will occasionally need control over not only its own events, but also its own separate state.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] LiveComponents have their own `mount/1` and `handle_event/3` callbacks, as well as their own state with change tracking support, similar to LiveViews.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] They are lightweight since they "run" in the same process as the parent LiveView, but are more complex than function components themselves.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Given they all run in the same process, errors in components cause the whole view to fail to render.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] For a complete rundown, see `Phoenix.LiveComponent`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] When in doubt over Functional components or live components?, default to the former.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Rely on the latter only when you need the additional state.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Finally, if you want complete isolation between parts of a LiveView, you can always render a LiveView inside another LiveView by calling `live_render/3`.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] This child LiveView runs in a separate process than the parent, with its own callbacks.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] If a child LiveView crashes, it won't affect the parent.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] If the parent crashes, all children are terminated.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] When rendering a child LiveView, the `:id` option is required to uniquely identify the child.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] A child LiveView will only ever be rendered and mounted a single time, provided its ID remains unchanged.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] To force a child to re-mount with new session data, a new ID must be provided.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] Given that it runs in its own process, a nested LiveView is an excellent tool for creating completely isolated UI elements, but it is a slightly expensive abstraction if all you want is to compartmentalize markup or events (or both).
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] This documentation is split into two categories.
[src:phoenix-liveview/welcome] We have the API reference for all LiveView modules, that's where you will learn more about `Phoenix.Component`, `Phoenix.LiveView`, and so on.
